    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*What is the relationship between low income restaurant health scores and health inspector bias?*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Research Gate states that in large cities such as Chicago, low income neighborhoods take the short end of the city's budget (1). Because of this discrepancy, it is believed that \n",
    "lower income restaurants do not receive the higher quality health inspection. This relates to my research question because I am trying to see if because of this budget, that there is a difference in health inspector bias towards lower income restaurants who need government support in order to run.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the review by Jennifer J. Quinlan seen on The Sustainabilist, she states that \"low income populations are more likely to experience greater rates of gastrointestinal illness\". This relates to my research question because by looking at data, you can notice if health inspection scores are lower in low income areas, which could directly correlate to why low income populations have more foodborne illnesses. Knowing this could improve the government's financial support towards low income restaurants that are already less privileged because of their low income.\n",
    "References (include links):\n",
    "- 1)https://www.researchgate.net/publication/255975675_Foodborne_Illness_Incidence_Rates_and_Food_Safety_Risks_for_Populations_of_Low_Socioeconomic_Status_and_Minority_RaceEthnicity_A_Review_of_the_Literature\n",
    "- 2)https://www.sustainabilist.com/blog/chicago-data-analysis-a-internship-project"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "My hypothesis is that there will be health inspector bias with low income restaurant health scores. This is because according to my background sources, the lack of government funding behind low income restaurants can lead to a lack of improved health resources for those restaurants. My hypothesis is also supported through Jennifer Quinlan's review article, where it was found that lower income populations have a higher chance of contracting foodborne illnesses which can correlate to lower health scores in restaurants in those areas."
