    "# Ethics & Privacy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*Fill in your ethics & privacy discussion here*\n",
    "A privacy concern that my question could pose is the exposure of the restaurants with low health scores. This could lead to people avoiding these restaurants because they explicitly see what their health score is. Usually (or at least in my experience), when people show up at restaurants, they're there for the taste of the food, and not the health score, it's not people's main focus. So when a research paper comes out with restaurant's health scores exposed, this would be unethical and lacks privacy for the restaurants. This could also sway restaurants from participating in the study because of the exposure. To solve this problem, I believe anonymity would be the best solution, as this is a focus mainly on health inspector bias than the restaurant itself. Though anonymity may discredit my data a bit, I believe protection in restaurants that are already low income is needed, so that they do not lose the little business they already have. \n",
    "\n",
    "If data was collected, this could be where potential biases can arise. I may miss out on certain low income restaurants in the low income areas, as there are many small businesses that aren't listed online such as Google or Yelp. Though this problem can't be completely solved, I believe maybe asking locals around the area could be a great way to get a feel for the super underground restaurants."
